The import command triggers a file dialog that allows the user to
select the CSV file to import. Users are likely to type in a file
path wrongly, hence the choice of a file dialog.

The export command allows the user to input a file name to save the
records to. The export command parser ensures that file names
provided are valid and will save to the "/exports" folder in CSV
format.

Currently, the import command only triggers a file dialog and
displays the name of the file selected, while the export command
creates an empty file with the file name provided. Future work
includes implementing the CSV parser to write the address book
in CSV format, as well as parse the CSV file into the address
book.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add CSV parser to parse and unparse CSV files into AddressBooks.
commitResults.messageBody:
Summary of main changes/additions:
- Abstract out AdaptedPerson, SerializableAddressBook since
  CSV variants can share common functions with the existing JSON
  variants
- Create CsvUtil to handle reading and writing CSV files
- Create CsvFile class as an abstraction of CSV file data, so that
  operations can be performed on it e.g. creating a string stream
  of its contents, querying for values in rows without knowing the
  index (guards against column positional changes), etc.
- Add CSV test data files to test the read/write abilities of the
  program
- Add a method in FileUtil to write a stream of strings into a file
  using a BufferedWriter, so that larger write operations can be
  handled without running out of memory
- Create CsvAdaptedPerson as an intermediate class between the Person
  class and its CSV serialisation. Methods for parsing CSV values into
  the Person class are also contained inside CsvAdaptedPerson, so that
  changes to the Person class can be minimised to CsvAdaptedPerson
- Improve CommandResult messages to reflect scenario outcomes more
  accurately

Refactor CsvFile::addRow() method to accept CsvParsable interface
commitResults.messageBody:
Previously, the method required the user to supply a List, from which
string values can be obtained by invoking the list's objects' toString()
method. However, there may be some objects for which the toString()
method does not return the desired string representation.

By changing the parameter to be of CsvParsable type, objects that
want to serialize into CSV must implement CsvParsable::getCsvValues(),
which returns a List of Strings. This provides greater control over
the string representation of the values.

Add delimiter specifier in generated CSV files
commitResults.messageBody:
The semicolon is an uncommon separator, and other spreadsheet applications
may have difficulty identifying it and instead look for a comma to delimit.

By adding sep=; in the first line of the CSV file, other applications can
recognise the separator and parse the file correctly, thus requiring no
further configurations in order to read the file.

Additionally, by identifying the delimiter from the first line of the CSV
file, non-semicolon-delimited files can also be read into HRMate.

commitResults.messageBody: Fix Glossary hyperlink in UG not working
Make the command word case-insensitive

Summary of key changes:

Person and Leave field constructors' method signatures now indicate
that they will throw IllegalValueException for inputs that fail
validation. This will reduce the likelihood of unhandled exceptions
as the compiler can better detect these exceptions.

ParserUtil methods will handle most of these exceptions thrown
by the constructors, such that the only exception that will be
thrown/bubbled from ParserUtil methods are ParseExceptions. This
reduces the need for exception handling by methods that call
ParserUtil methods, streamlining exception handling and reducing
the chance of an unhandled exception propagating further.

EditLeaveDescriptor will not allow a end date before a start date.
This ensures that at no point in time will the descriptor allow
such a state, thereby reducing the likelihood of accidental bugs.

EditLeaveCommandParser::parse has been refactored to reduce the
length of the method for improved readability.

Removed NullPointerException declaration in ParserUtil::parseName
signature. The developer should never pass in a null value as an
argument, hence it should be treated as an assertion rather than
an exception to be handled.

With the change in error handling of ParserUtil, error messages
for commands with indices must be updated to reflect the correct
nature of the error. Overflow and out-of-bound indices have their
own error messages.

Additional changes include modifying the message contents to improve
helpfulness, and modifying Messages::format(Leave) to only show
the description if there is a non-empty description.

AddLeaveCommandParser::parse is modified to use if-else instead of
stream operations, as Stream::map is unable to handle ParseException.

All changes related to Messages::format(Leave) have been reverted to
avoid violating feature flaw. Note that this means that all leaves
printed in CommandResult will not feature the Description field.

Other changes include renaming the variables containing the error
messages - Messages.java from the master branch was used instead
to remove all modified error messages from this branch.

commitResults.messageTitle: Revert changes about improved index parsing
commitResults.messageBody:
Commit d447735 had changes that improved index parsing, which would
allow it to distinguish between an integer overflow and a
non-numeric index. These changes have been reverted, along with
their test cases, as the overflow scenario would have thrown a
different error message, a violation of the feature freeze.

commitResults.messageTitle: Fix leaves' employees not updating their names
commitResults.messageBody:
Leave::belongsTo previously used equals, which is an issue as there
is no guarantee that the employee field in the leave contains the
same instance as the employee list. By changing it to use
ComparablePerson::isSamePerson instead, only the name will be
compared, thus fixing the bug.

Test cases were added for Leave and EditCommandIntegrationTest
to guarantee that the code produces the desired behaviour.

commitResults.messageTitle: (WIP) Implement unit tests for JsonSerializableLeavesBook and JsonAdaptedLeave classes
commitResults.messageBody:
Current situation:
* Prior to converting a JsonAdaptedLeave object into a Leave object to be stored
in the LeavesBook, there must be a check at some point in time during the
conversion with the AddressBook to ensure that the person whose name is noted
in the Leave object corresponds to a record in the address book itself.

* Going into this implementation, I plan to leave this check to be done at as
high an abstraction level as possible, as opposed to passing the addressbook into
the JsonAdaptedLeave to check things. However, without passing the addressbook into
JsonAdaptedLeave, I am unable to convert the name into a corresponding Person object
in the JsonAdaptedLeave level.

* Instead, I have opted to expose these fields to the JsonSerializableLeavesBook level
instead, which will take the addressBook in the toModelType()
method to convert the JsonAdaptedLeave objects into Leave objects

* By doing so, I have broken the layers of abstraction in the JsonAdaptedLeave class,
and as a result I am unable to properly test it. Do note that the current toModelType()
method of the JsonAdaptedLeave class also does not work and returns null.

* This current block prevents me from writing the remaining unit tests for these two classes
